[normal]Annex I – 
[normal]CBI response
[normal] 
[normal]The Future of Apprenticeships in England: Next Steps from the Richard Review
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To underpin a truly demand-led system, businesses and ministers need to devise a much simpler funding system that will empower employers to bring in high-quality provision that is relevant and directly addresses the needs of their business[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Businesses should be trusted to set the expected standards that underpin the apprenticeship programme[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is an urgent need to refocus the system so that it responds effectively to the demands of business. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Exhibit 1: Employers are invested in apprenticeships that deliver substantial new skills[bold]“As a company, serving an industry that relies on having a skilled, competent and qualified workforce to deliver its business objectives, a successful apprenticeship scheme has been and continues to be a key focus of our strategy. [Company name] takes its investment in its people very seriously with the engineering academy being just one part of our learning and development offering, with our leadership academy forming the other part”.  
[normal]HR Director, Engineering Firm[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]“People are an absolute priority for [company name] and fundamental to our success. Central to our vision and aspirations is our policy of providing career opportunities that allow all employees to develop to their full potential. [Company name] invests over £30million annually in training our employees as they must be 
[normal]expertly skilled to fulfil the high expectations of our customers. For their hard work and achievements our employees deserve to be recognised beyond our company.” 
[normal]Education Manager, Retailer[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Businesses have the appetite for greater involvement in the apprenticeships system, but we need structures at the national and local level to harness employer involvement[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Exhibit 2: The UKCES Employer Ownership of Skills Pilots[bold]Nissan[bold]The north east based car manufacturer is set to need 2,000 new staff to meet production demands over the next two years, a huge challenge given regional skills shortages and a need to boost skills levels in a supply chain that provides around 80% of its components. Their winning EOP bid will see Nissan develop four new training programmes to boost skills at all levels of the organisation from existing workers to new recruits and across their supply chain.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Siemens [bold]The successful bid of CBI member Siemens will see them work with organisations including sector skills council Semta to extend its re-employment and apprenticeship programmes to its key suppliers – a great example of how innovative skills provision can support a sector
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Improving trust and confidence requires high standards of inspection and rigorous assessment, but the government should avoid proxies for quality unless driven by demand from businesses[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The road to apprenticeships should not just start at 16. As part of a more coherent system, business wants improved careers advice and clear routes into technical education from 14, alongside tougher, new gold standard vocational “A-levels” at 18[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
